{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> κῆρυξ</b>, ῡκος, ὁ, <br /> <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <b>κᾶρυξ</b> [ᾱ] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 20a. 2, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 8.1 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]:—but <b>κήρῡκος</b>, ου, ὁ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Etymologicum Magnum” 775.26 \">Refs</a>]: (κηρύσσω):— <b>herald, pursuivant</b>: generally, <b>public messenger, envoy</b>, κ. λιγύφθογγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.50, +others; κηρύκων, οἳ δημιοεργοὶ ἔασιν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.135; κ. Διῒφίλοι 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.517; κ., Διὸς ἄγγελοι ἠδὲ καὶ ἀνδρῶν 1.334 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; θεῶν κ., of Hermes, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 80, compare “Th.” 939, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 515, “Ch.” 124: distinguished from πρέσβεις\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], as being <b>messengers between nations at war</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"Scholia 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 1.29, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 727, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 941a, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 12.4: used interchangeably with ἀπόστολος, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.21 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: as <i>proper name</i> of a family at Athens, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.53, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.116, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.38.3, 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 8.103; functioning as μάγειροι at festivals, Clidem. 3, 17; Κηρυκίδαι 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__b</b></Level4> as <i>feminine</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 8.1, 4th-5th c.AD(?): Nonnus Epicus “Dionysiaca” 4.11. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>